ACCRA, GHANA = The u. S.
embassy has protested to Ghana's
foreign ministry against "scur-
rilous attacks on an American
Negro attache who replaced an
American flag torn down during
a Ghanaian demonstration.


The US. protest cited an ar
ticle in the governmental ontrol-
led Ghanaian Times which cri-
ticized the attache, A. Emerson
Player of Denver, for replacing
the banner. The paper said Play
er and other members of the u S.
embassy staff were engaged in
"nefarious activities"


The U. S. embassy said the at
tack on Player can only be deep
ly resented by all Americans,
whatever their color"

The Board of Trustees of Phoe-
nix Elementary School District
III granted Elder H. Russell,
School Social Worker at Lowell,
Booker T. Washington and Ade-
line Gray Schools, leave of Abb
sence for the l964-65 school
year. He will do graduate study
at the National University of
Mexico, Mexico City.


Mr.. Russell previously has
attended summer sessions at the
University of Arizona and this
full year leave will enable him
to complete a program of study
in the area of Social Anthro-
pology. He will devote special
attention to developing of Span
ish.

Roy L. Cooksey, 1912 Irene
Vista, Tucson, was recently nam
ed president of the Southwest
Area Conference of the National
Association for the Advancement
of Colored People.


Mr.. Cooksey moved to Arizona
% years ago from Ell Paso.
Texas. He worked in the days
and earned his yigh school GER
tificate at night classes at Tucson
High. He is now taking corre-
spondence course from the Uni
versity of Arizona. He hopes to
obtain degree in business ad-
ministration.


Mr.. Cooksey was one of the
first Negroes hired by the Am
erican Shelter and Refinery Co.,
and he has good record with
the firm.


Very active in civil rights
movements for the last decade,
Mr.. Cooksey is now serving his
third consecutive term as presi-
dent of the Pinal County Branch,
NAACP.


He was the first Negro appoint
ed to the state civil rights COM
mittee of the AFL-CIO Central
Trades Council and he is the
president of the Lillian Cavett
School PTA.


He has served seven years as
a Scoutmaster and attended the
National Jamboree in 1852 in
California.


The father of six children,
three boys and three girls, Mr..
Cooksey believes his efforts will
help make better world for his
family.


He and his wife received the
1868 Brotherhood Good Neigh
borhood Award from the National
Council of Christians and Jews.

Mahalia Jackson, one Of the
worlds greatest singers, will
appear in solo concert at Phoe-
nix Union High School auditorium
Feb. % at $3.50 pm.


Miss Jackson, whose appear
ance here is being sponsored by
the Phoenix Community and Civic
Concert Association, has per-
formed before sell-out audiences
in Carnegie Hall eight times and
has drawn CRITICAL and popular
acclaim through her many Eu-
ropean appearances.


Because Of her religious con-
Wctions, she refuses to sing
blues.


Gospel singing has brought
Miss Jackson fame. She started
life in poverty. the third of six
children. Her father worked as a
stevedore and a barber, and on
Sundays, was a preacher. The
family lived in New Orleans.


Miss Jackson had no musical
training, but sang in her fathers
church choir. At l6. she went to
Chicago where she was discover
ed singing with the choir of the
Greater Salem Baptist Church.


Her first single record, "Move
Up Little Higher" sold more
than two million copies and each
of her 10 subsequent albums has
sold more than the two million
mark.


Tickets for Miss Jackson s
performance here may be OBJ
tanned at the Linde Box Office in
the Sahara Hotel, the Sombrero
Playhouse, Remers Gift Shops
in Park Central and Christ-Town,
and the Desert Squire in Scots
dale.

The bout will be televised di-
rectly from Miami Beach, Fla,
to the Playground arena by the
Closed Circuit Corporation of
America on Tuesday, Feb. Is.
The fight will also be seen
at the Fox Theater by Antenna-
vision. Promoter is Dick Smith.

Advanced ticket sales for the
Sonny Liston = Cassius Clay
world heavyweight boxing champ
ionship bout are being sold at the
Arizona State Playground, re-
ported promoter Jim Sexton.
